OK, my Samsung Galaxy Nexus phone doesn't have buttons like my PS Vita, but I straight loved "Rayman Jungle Run". It got game details and gameplay familiarities of its predecessor, "Rayman Origins", right. Ubisoft just made my night!   The new update adds more levels and updates the UI.

I'm a huge Rayman fan, so it's great to be able to play anytime on my Android.  While not having a dpad may seem odd for a platformer, it really isn't an issue for Rayman.  If you've done the treasure chest chases in Origins or the music based levels in Legends, you know your just holding right on the dpad while keeping the run button pressed down anyway, so this game is basically the same idea but it runs automatically.  The graphics are beautiful, but it doesn't always hold up.  I did experience times of slowdown, especially in the dead levels on my Droid RAZR Maxx HD, which is a pretty new phone.  I'm not sure what the issue is.  Obviously Android is having a hard time allocating resources between the app and the stuff running in the background.  Not sure who controls this, but you would hope the game developer would be able to tell the operating system how much resources are required.  That being said, most of the time the game runs great, and for $0.99, I think it's well worth it.  Some people have complained about ads, and Ubisoft was saying this was a bug.  I've had ads pop up a handful of times from the main menu.  It looks to me like that is something Ubisoft was toying with as an idea for a free version of the game, and somehow they didn't get the code removed properly.  It doesn't happen very often, so no big deal.

A couple of significant ways in which this lighter mobile version differs from the critically acclaimed "Rayman Origins" are: ‚Ä¢ To simplify and make it touch device friendly, the d-pad is done away with, reducing required player input to just jumping and attacking. The running is done for you. ‚Ä¢ As the title suggests, all levels are (almost) exclusively jungles. One glitch I found is that if you don't give the app a fresh re-start, when you come back to it, the sprite planes are missing textures, showing just a bunch of blank rectangles. This shouldn't, however, discourage you from getting this outstanding must-have masterpiece!

I see a lot of people giving one star reviews to this game due to the fact that the update erased old save files. Okay, yes, that really happened. You'll have to play it again from the start.  But did the game actually become bad suddenly? Is it now not functioning properly? It's still working, it's still amazing and fun and the graphics are still lovely. And to top it off, you now have new levels to play.  It's a game, people. You're supposed to play it. It's not like someone erased your life's work. Sure, mention the fact in your reviews, warn people, that's fine. Knock off a star, I understand that. But don't switch to one star ratings because you've lost your progress.  To all those who are considering buying this game, just go for it. It's fun and looks pretty much amazing. Don't let the sudden onslaught of vitriol in the reviews deprive you of playing what is probably one of the best arcade titles on Google Play.

Although it would be nice to have a fully controllable Rayman platformer, this is really great for what it is. I usually get bored of one touch running/jumping games very quickly, but this has got a lot more to it than the usual fare. For one thing the graphics are absolutely lovely, and although it lags occasionally on my ancient Nexus S, on the whole it runs fairly smoothly. The levels have a variety of obstacles that make the game varied and interesting, and so far I haven't come across any Yoo Ninja-style horrific moments of frustrating madness (though I'm only a few levels into the game, so we'll see how that goes!) - it's challenging but in a very fun way indeed. Basically it's a great little fun game, definitely well worth the price, so I would definitely recommend it. Just be aware that on top of the 77 MB download, you need around 160-170 MB of free space (which the description doesn't mention) for additional files. All in all, a right old goodun. Pretty much the best game in the run and touch/jump genre (or whatever you call it), but Sonic CD is still holds the overall title for the king of Android platformers!

I was a HUGE fan of Rayman Origins.  Everything including the art design, the music, and the gameplay were so flawless!  I was so happy to see this game find its way on to android. The game play is simple, fun (works great for touchscreen gaming, which I am still a bit reluctant to fully embrace), and addicting.  Trying to collect all the lums for each level is a challenge you'll actually enjoy doing, rather than it seeming like a completion chore.  Even though the music and environments are rehashed from Origins, they are so well done it's great to enjoy them again.  GET THIS GAME- easily worth the $2.99.  Also, if you haven't played it, get Rayman Origins (xbox360, ps3, wii)- a seriously underrated game which I guarantee you will have blast playing.
